I&#x27;m no good at Ada, but I like the way it&#x27;s syntax tries to guide you through reading the program. Now for something of comparative complexity in Clojure:<p><pre><code>  (def x (ref 1))

  (defn increment [i]
    (if (> i 0) 
      (
        (dosync
          (alter x inc)
        )
        (Thread/sleep 1)
        (increment (- i 1))
      )
    )
  )

  (defn decrement [i]
    (if (> i 0)
      (
        (dosync
          (alter x dec)
        )
        (Thread/sleep 1)
        (decrement (- i 1))
      )
    )
  )

  (defn printref [i]
    (if (> i 0) 
      (
        (dosync
          (println (format &quot;in printref %d&quot; @x))
        )
        (Thread/sleep 1)
        (printref (- i 1))
      )
    )
  )

  (future
    (increment 10)
  )

  (future
    (printref 15)
  ) 

  (future
    (decrement 10)
  )
</code></pre>
Isn&#x27;t this much nicer? It&#x27;s not immediately obvious that x is an atomic variable, but aside from that it&#x27;s a lot better than the Haskell example. It took me along the lines of 2-3 hours from never having touched a Lisp to writing this.

